    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Bank, Southampton,</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Jan 1 <hi rend="print">18</hi>80</date>
                    <salute>My dear Father,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>It is a nuisance to have these bonds paid off; the simplest way is to sell them as the Manager proposes.</p>
                    <p>$10,000 = £2040<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
                    <p>why not buy $10,000 Pennsylvania General Mortgage payable 1910 price is 127—therefore $10,000 will cost £2540 or $8000 will cost £2035 or, and will pay 4<formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math></formula> per cent.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>Or Massachusetts state loan 5 per cent <hi rend="underline">payable in gold</hi> as follows</p>
<p>1891—at 109</p>
<p>1895 at 111</p>
<p>1900 at 114</p>
<p>are <hi rend="underline">perfectly</hi> safe, if they can be bought.</p>
                    <p>Metropolitan 3<formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></formula> per cent Stock<ref target="#foot.f4"/> is at 105<formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></formula> and will only pay 3<formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math></formula> percent.</p>
<p>or Baltimore &amp; Ohio 6 per cent Mortgage pay<hi rend="superscript">ble</hi>. 1910 at 121 is I believe quite safe.</p>
<p>Your affect son | W. E. Darwin</p>
                    <p>P.S. <hi rend="underline">Southampton Dock</hi><ref target="#foot.f5"/></p>
<p>Debenture 4<formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></formula> per cent</p>
                    <p>Stock is at 110</p>
<p>The liabilities of the company are as follows.</p>
<p>£82 300 Mortgage Deb<hi rend="superscript">es</hi>.</p>
<p>£217.700 4<formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></formula> per cent Deb: Stock</p>
<p>£1,165,625 ordinary &amp; pref<hi rend="superscript">ce</hi> Stock</p>
<p>so that the Deb: Stock should be quite safe</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="annotations">
                <note><hi rend="italic">Verso of 3d page</hi>: ‘3 [<hi rend="italic">circled pencil</hi>] First Mortgage | Bonds of Illinois Central R’ <hi rend="italic">pencil</hi>; ‘11 [<hi rend="italic">circled pencil</hi>] City of Boston Bonds | if to run about [<hi rend="italic">interl</hi>] ten years’<ref target="#foot.f6"/> <hi rend="italic">pencil</hi></note>
            </div>

            
            
             
            
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">William wrote ‘1880’ in error; the year is established by the reference to bonds bought and sold in CD’s Investment book and Account books (see nn. 2 and 3 below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD had purchased Pennsylvania Central Railway bonds in 1852; these were sold in January 1881 for £2044 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 5<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. (CD’s Investment book (Down House MS), pp. 61, 110).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD bought ‘Pennsylvania R. General Mortgage Bonds’ for £1980 in January 1881 (CD’s Account books–banking account (Down House MS)).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">In 1870 and 1871, CD had purchased ‘Metropolitan consolidated stock’, which paid 3 <formula>
                <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>
            </formula> per cent; he purchased more in December 1881 (CD’s Investment book (Down House MS), pp. 136, 166).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">The Southampton Dock Company had been formed in 1836 to build docks in the port; it continued to manage the docks until 1892, when ownership passed to the London and South Western Railway Company (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_11260.xml">Roussel 2009</ref>, pp. 12, 17). </note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">The notes are for CD’s reply of <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12973.xml">3 January [1881]</ref>. </note>
        </div>
    
